===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|countable|often with ''of'', typically of adverse results}} The [[source]] of, or [[reason]] for, an event or action; that which produces or effects a result.
#: ''They identified a burst pipe as the '''cause''' of the flooding.''
#* {{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=5
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=He was thinking; but the glory of the song, the swell from the great organ, the clustered lights, […], the height and vastness of this noble fane, its antiquity and its strength—all these things seemed to have their part as '''causes''' of the thrilling emotion that accompanied his thoughts.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|especially with ''for'' and a bare noun}} Sufficient reason for a state, as of emotion.
#: ''There is no '''cause''' for alarm.''
#: ''The end of the war was a '''cause''' for celebration.
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[goal]], [[aim]] or [[principle]], especially one which [[transcend]]s purely [[selfish]] ends.
#* {{rfdate|and other bibliographic particulars}} {{w|Shakespeare}}
#*: God befriend us, as our '''cause''' is just.
#* {{rfdate|and other bibliographic particulars}} {{w|Burke}}
#*: The part they take against me is from zeal to the '''cause'''.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Sake; interest; advantage.
#* Bible, 2 Corinthians vii. 12
#*: I did it not for his '''cause'''.
# {{lb|en|countable|obsolete}} Any subject of discussion or debate; a matter; an affair.
#* {{rfdate|and other bibliographic particulars}} Shakespeare
#*: What counsel give you in this weighty '''cause'''?
# {{lb|en|countable|legal}} A [[suit]] or [[action]] in court; any legal process by which a party endeavors to obtain his claim, or what he regards as his right; case; ground of action.

